# Jira Mandatory Fields: AC, DoR, DoD, Business Value

When creating or updating any Jira issue, the following four fields are **always required** and must **always be set as custom fields, and custom fields only.** They are never duplicated in the description body, for any issue type ‚Äî this applies uniformly to Initiative, Epic, Story, Task, Test, Defect, and (where the screen allows) Sub-task.

| Field | Custom Field ID |
|---|---|
| Business Value | `customfield_11491` |
| Acceptance Criteria | `customfield_10515` |
| Definition of Ready | `customfield_16516` |
| Definition of Done | `customfield_16544` |

## Rule (updated 2026-07-22 ‚Äî supersedes the old "both places" rule for Epic/Initiative)

**Every issue type, including Epic and Initiative: custom field only.** Do **not** add `## Business Value`, `## Acceptance Criteria`, `## Definition of Ready`, or `## Definition of Done` headings to the description ‚Äî the dedicated custom field is the single source of truth and duplicating it in free text is redundant.

This was confirmed safe on Epics: all 4 custom fields were verified settable via `jira_update_issue` across 36 real Infra Epics/Initiatives on 2026-07-22 (e.g. `LATC-5803`, `LATC-5101`), including a live backfill of a previously-empty `customfield_11491` on an Epic. The earlier belief that these fields were "untested/unconfirmed on the Epic screen" was wrong ‚Äî they work exactly like Story/Task. Epics/Initiatives now follow the same custom-field-only policy as sprint-level issues; keep the narrative body (Problem/Opportunity, Outcomes, Scope, Out of scope, Stakeholders, etc.) in the description, but never the four governance fields.

**Screen-availability exception (confirmed 2026-07-17, still applies):** this Jira DC's screen scheme does not expose all 4 fields on every sprint-level type:
- **Sub-task**: none of the 4 fields (AC/DoR/DoD/BV) exist on that screen ‚Äî keep all 4 as `##` headings in the description instead. **Out of scope for active enforcement:** by explicit direction, Sub-task field compliance is deprioritized ‚Äî don't flag existing Sub-tasks as gaps needing a fix, and don't spend effort chasing this further until told otherwise. New Sub-tasks should still get the description-heading fallback as a matter of course (it's free and correct), just don't treat it as a required remediation pass.
- **Task**: AC/DoR/DoD exist and work fine; **Business Value does not exist on the Task screen** ‚Äî keep `## Business Value` in the description for Tasks only.
- **Story, Epic, Initiative**: all 4 fields work fine via custom field (Business Value on Story is create-then-edit; on Epic/Initiative it has been observed working on update ‚Äî attempt at create, and if rejected, immediately follow up with `jira_update_issue`).

When a field genuinely has no screen slot for that issue type (currently only: Business Value on Task; all 4 on Sub-task), don't drop the content and don't force a doomed API call ‚Äî put it in the description under its original heading. This is the only sanctioned case of duplicating these fields in free text.

**Active enforcement scope:** Epic, Initiative, Story, and Task are the issue types actively enforced end-to-end. Sub-task is intentionally out of scope for now per the note above.

Also for all issue types: don't use separate `## Context` / `## Goal` / `## Approach` headings either. Instead lead the description with a condensed narrative (for Epic/Initiative: Problem/Opportunity, Outcomes, Scope; for sprint-level issues: a 1‚Äì3 sentence summary, no heading needed), then keep any remaining sections that have no dedicated field (e.g. `## Out of scope`, `## Links`, `## Stakeholders`, `## Outcomes (value unlocked)`).

## General rules (all issue types)

1. **Always set the custom field** via `additional_fields` in `jira_create_issue` or `jira_update_issue`.
2. **Never leave the custom field empty or placeholder-only** ‚Äî generate real, task-specific content based on context if the user hasn't provided it.
3. `customfield_11491` (Business Value) has been confirmed **rejected on the Story/Task create screen** but **accepted on the edit screen** ‚Äî attempt it on create, and if rejected, immediately follow up with a `jira_update_issue` call to set it rather than dropping it silently. Epics/Initiatives can generally have it set directly via `jira_update_issue`; attempt at create too and fall back to update if rejected.

## Hard Stop

If you are about to call `jira_create_issue` or `jira_update_issue` and any of these four fields is missing or blank in its custom field, **stop and fill it first.** Never fill the gap by writing it into the description instead ‚Äî the only exceptions are the confirmed missing-screen-slot cases above (Business Value on Task; all four on Sub-task).
